{"id": "food_FOOD00612", "name": "Grape wine (food medium)", "category": "food", "organism_scope": "food microbiome / general", "aerobic": true, "description": "Food-derived medium: metabolizable components of Grape wine [Beverages] from FooDB, plus a standard M9 mineral base. Organic components use presence-based uptake bounds; FooDB content retained. Measured compounds with no BiGG exchange are listed under uncovered.", "namespace": "bigg", "provenance": {"source_type": "database", "citation": "FooDB v2020-04-07 (Wishart DS et al., foodb.ca). Content sources: 22397579, 22397579; USDA (con), 22397579; USDA(con), DTU, MANUAL, Ough, CS. (1984) Volatile nitrogen compounds in fermented beverages. In: Nykänen, L. & Lehtonen, P., eds, Flavour Research of Alcoholic Beverages, Vol. 3, Instrumental and Sensory Analysis, Helsinki, Foundation for Biotechnical and Industrial Fermentation Research, pp. 199-225, PHENOL EXPLORER, USDA.", "doi": "", "url": "https://foodb.ca/downloads", "notes": "Organic components mapped from FooDB compounds to BiGG via InChIKey/name. Mineral base added. Bounds presence-based; foodb_content retained. Unmapped measured compounds kept in uncovered (v2 completeness fix). IMPORTANT: composition values are taken from the archived FooDB 2020-04-07 CSV data release; FooDB's live food page no longer displays this bulk composition, so it will appear empty. Verify individual compounds via the per-component cross-reference links. Underlying content was aggregated by FooDB from USDA / DTU / Phenol Explorer.", "data_release": "FooDB 2020-04-07 CSV release (foodb.ca/downloads)", "food_record": "https://foodb.ca/foods/FOOD00612", "verification": "expert-curated (multi-source food composition; growth-relevant profile completed, FooDB noise removed)", "curation_date": "2026-07-17", "curation_sources": [], "curation_notes": "Dominant carbon/energy sources are ethanol (~105 g/L) then glycerol (~10.5 g/L); dominant organic acid is tartaric (~2.7 g/L) with malic/succinic/lactic/succinic and acetic secondary. The FooDB record was missing every major wine organic acid (tartaric, malic, succinic, lactic, acetic, citric) - the key curation gain here. Residual sugars are low (dry wine, ~6 g/L total, fructose>glucose). Proline is the dominant free amino acid. Values are for a dry red table wine (USDA FDC 173190); white/sweet", "curation_added": ["L-tartaric acid (dominant wine acid, ~2.7 g/L)", "L-malic acid (~1.27 g/L)", "succinic acid (~1.15 g/L)", "L-lactic acid (~0.80 g/L)", "acetic acid (~0.40 g/L)", "citric acid (~0.12 g/L)", "glycerol quantified (~10.5 g/L)", "ethanol quantified (~105 g/L)", "D-glucose and D-fructose split with amounts", "L-proline and L-arginine quantified", "quantified USDA vitamin and mineral panel"], "curation_removed": [{"name": "Cholesterol", "reason": "Animal sterol; biologically implausible in a grape/yeast fermentation product. FooDB predicted, not measured. USDA reports 0 mg cholesterol in wine."}, {"name": "Retinol", "reason": "Preformed (animal) vitamin A; absent in wine. USDA reports 0 vitamin A activity. FooDB grape-carryover artifact."}, {"name": "Beta-Carotene", "reason": "Grape-skin carotenoid essentially absent in finished wine (USDA vitamin A ~0); FooDB grape-derived prediction, not a growth nutrient of wine."}, {"name": "Lutein", "reason": "Grape carotenoid negligible in finished wine; FooDB grape-carryover, not a measured wine nutrient."}, {"name": "Phytomenadione", "reason": "Vitamin K1; USDA reports ~0 vitamin K in wine. FooDB grape-carryover, negligible."}, {"name": "Iron (Fe3+)", "reason": "Redundant duplicate speciation of iron; consolidated into single 'iron' entry (USDA Fe 0.46 mg/100 g)."}, {"name": "Fe2+ mitochondria", "reason": "Compartment-tagged duplicate of iron from a model namespace; not a distinct wine nutrient."}, {"name": "O2 O2", "reason": "Dissolved oxygen is near-zero in finished/bottled wine (reductive storage); not a defining medium component."}], "curation_confidence